Article One editorial board

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Two cases confirmed in Hong Kong

The new type of pneumonia has drawn attention from all over the territory and the world. Various sectors in Hong Kong have been discussing the changes in the epidemic situation and the measures to deal with it.

On December 30th the mainland for the first time reported pneumonia of unknown origin in Wuhan. Hong Kong newspaper and online media, Hong Kong 01, Ming Pao Daily News, South China Morning Post, Duan Media and other media have set up special reports since December 31, and continue to update. In particular, since January 20, there have been hundreds of suspected cases in Hong Kong, and the subject has been updated almost hourly.

Special topics on epidemic situation in south China Morning Post

TVB television news

This is a reporter reporting live from West Kowloon Terminus, Phoenix satellite TV

And Hong Kong TVB, Cable Television, Phoenix satellite TV and other major television stations, news channels 24-hour long broadcast about pneumonia, and the use of rolling subtitles, real-time updates on the number of people infected and the latest news. When press conferences are held on the latest news of pneumonia, they even interrupt the original program to interrupt the live broadcast of the press conference.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Wuhan pneumonia accounts for 2 / 3 of Ming Pao instant news

Major media revealed a number of loopholes in the epidemic prevention work and to be strengthened.

January 21st, hong Kong 01 pointed out that "many of the Hong Kong government's port screening measures are still limited to Wuhan, which is obviously not rigorous and safe enough. Instead, all groups coming to Hong Kong should have temperature screening and health declaration at all entry points. ".

But Hong Kong's swift response to the outbreak can also be seen in the headlines.

Orange News on January 21st released a timeline of the response to pneumonia in Hong Kong and the mainland, showing the wary speed with which the city's government, after Atypical pneumonia, has responded.

Hong Kong 01 reports new pneumonia

Compared with Wuhan's previous calm, Taiwan and Hong Kong have remained relatively tense, Duan said. In the Taipei Songshan Airport, LED screens scroll to warn: "When traveling to Wuhan and nearby areas, personal hygiene measures such as washing hands frequently with soap, wearing a mask for coughing should be implemented" , and to remind tourists to seek medical attention promptly if they develop these suspected symptoms.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Comparison of pneumonia and SARS in Wuhan

The coverage can be divided into four main categories: follow-up on the epidemic situation, the corresponding measures of the Hong Kong government, international response measures, and the impact of the epidemic on Hong Kong's economy.

1. Confirm the diagnosis

According to Hong Kong 01, the first highly suspected case in Hong Kong was reported on January 22. The case involved a Wuhan passenger arriving from the mainland by high-speed rail. He was confirmed to have a fever upon his arrival in Hong Kong on the evening of January 21. According to the news, the passenger was first sent to the Queen Elizabeth Hospital, was Transferred to Princess Margaret Hospital on the evening of the 22nd. The patient was accompanied by a family of five who had stayed at the Royal Joy Hotel in Tsim Sha Tsui on the evening of the 21st. Four family members of the patient have flown to the Philippines.

On January 22, there was a second highly suspected case in Hong Kong involving a 56-year-old man from Hong Kong who had been to Wuhan.

On 23 January, both patients were diagnosed with novel pneumonia.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Maclehose Holiday Village will be used as quarantine area

2. Measures

On January 22, Hong Kong closed Lady maclehose Holiday Village, which was used as an isolation camp during the SARS outbreak in 2003, for quarantine purposes, according to Ming Pao.

The Hong Kong Tourism Board has cancelled the International Chinese New Year Extravaganza from the first day of the Lunar New Year to the fourth day of the Lunar New Year, as well as the Lunar New Year Cup soccer match on the second day of the Lunar New Year, to avoid large crowds.

3. International response to the Wuhan outbreak

London's Heathrow Airport will have a separate arrival area for flights from COVID-19 areas, UK Transport Secretary Chagrin said on January 22, Hong Kong 01 reported.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Hong Kong 01 reports new pneumonia affecting economy

4. Economic impact of the outbreak

Hong Kong 01 reported that while people are concerned about whether the epidemic on the mainland will spread further, they are also concerned about whether the economic impact of SARS in 2003 will be repeated.

February 2003, "SARS" into Hong Kong, the city nearly paralyzed, the greatest impact on Hong Kong's consumption and services exports. When the Chinese authorities opened the Individual Visit Scheme after SARS in 2003, Hong Kong's economy recovered quickly and unemployment dropped rapidly.

New type of pneumonia confirmed a news, has been the property market buyers worried about the future price trend, decided to "look at the first again" , and finally canceled the sale. The analysis worries that if the new type of pneumonia becomes more prevalent due to the decrease in mainland tourists, local people will not dare to go out and spend, so as to avoid crowded places, which may further impact on the retail, catering and consumption sectors in Hong Kong.

On January 23, Hong Kong shares fell nearly 500 points on news of a worsening outbreak of new pneumonia and the closure of Wuhan. Airline, hotel and travel-related shares all down.

The Bank of America released a report saying that in the new crisis, China has been more proactive in updating the situation, and that the situation is expected to have less impact on the stock market than SARS, based on factors such as the authorities'quick response and low mortality rates.

Director of the Center for Disease Control and Prevention, Macau Health Bureau, Lin Song

On January 22, the first confirmed case of new pneumonia in Macau was a 52-year-old businesswoman from Wuhan. On January 23, Macau confirmed the second case, a 66-year-old man, a tourist from Wuhan.

Macao authorities to ensure adequate supply of local masks, in the evening of the 23rd, the implementation of the "protection mask program. ". Macao residents with identity cards can purchase masks provided by the health bureau at designated dispensaries. Each citizen can purchase up to 10 masks at a price of 8 Patacas 10, and can buy them again 10 days later.

On January 23, the Chief Executive of Macao congratulated yi-cheng and told the media that all Chinese New Year activities had been cancelled. He added that there was a total stock of 20 million masks in Macau, which was believed to be sufficient for Macao citizens to buy at cost. In addition, he Yicheng met with the mayor of Zhuhai on the 23rd to discuss cooperation arrangements on epidemic prevention.

News of new pneumonia reported by Australian Broadcasting Corporation

"One confirmed patient was not seriously ill, sometimes with or without fever, and did not have fever when he arrived at the hospital. But he did have a fever, he didn't have any other complaints, he didn't have coughing and nasal congestion, runny nose and difficulty breathing, and he didn't feel too sick himself."-- Director of the Macao Center for Disease Control and Prevention, lam CHUNG@ACTV

The chief executive, he Yicheng, said that if the outbreak continued to worsen, he Yicheng would not rule out the closure of the casinos. He Yicheng said that the government should prepare for the worst.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Crowds of macanese line up at pharmacies to buy supplies

One also spoke to a Macau resident about the situation. He said that the current order in Macau is normal, but the flow of people on the streets is significantly less than in the past:

"Five or six out of 10 people now wear masks. I saw about 10 people lined up at every pharmacy this morning, buying supplies like face masks. There will be concerns. We all planned to go back to the mainland to visit our family during the Spring Festival, but now we let the frail old people stay in Macao and try not to go out

Tōmori's news show 'crunch time' Explores Wuhan Pneumonia

On January 21, a new case of pneumonia was confirmed in Taiwan.

The emergence of loopholes in epidemic prevention has aroused great concern. The mainstream TV media in Taiwan, such as TVBS, Dongsen, Zhongtian, etc. , broadcast a 24-hour news broadcast, with each one-hour news segment covering nearly 30 minutes of the new type of pneumonia, experts are also invited to discuss the issue, including on political talk shows. Print media such as the Union, the free times and Ettoday have columns on the epidemic that are "constantly updated" , with updates every hour or two.

After the epidemic prevention propaganda, Taiwan people go into public places are wearing masks

An overview of the major media reports on the epidemic in Taiwan, focusing on epidemic prevention and the impact of the epidemic on people's livelihood, trying to minimize panic among the people, while not ignoring the infectivity of the virus, assessing their own situation, and reporting symptoms as soon as possible to prevent the spread of the epidemic.

The Taiwanese themselves have a habit of wearing masks, after an outbreak, it is easy to appeal to the public to wear masks and strengthen hygiene habits. There are even hospitals outside the temporary shelter, if people have doubts or fever can go to the consultation, do preliminary testing, do not need to go inside the hospital, so as not to cause infection.

Tōmori went to Wuhan to report on the outbreak

As the first case of the new type of pneumonia in Taiwan was a female Taiwanese businessman in Wuhan, the government has put Wuhan Tourism on the highest alert and suspended all Wuhan tour groups from going to Taiwan.

Regarding the 55-year-old female Taiwanese businessman in Hubei Province who has been diagnosed, various media are actively following up the report. She worked as an educator in Wuhan and developed fever and cough on January 11. She bought medicine for herself for nine days because she did not trust local medical treatment. She did not fly back to Taiwan until January 20. She took the initiative to inform quarantine officers at Taoyuan airport of her symptoms, he was rushed to the hospital, where he was diagnosed with pneumonia and diagnosed with COVID-19.

The patient is in a stable condition with rapid breathing and requires oxygen mask and infusion. He is in a negative pressure isolation ward without intubation or cardiopulmonary bypass.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Taiwan media reports new type of pneumonia: refuting rumors, do not create panic, but also remind the public not to ignore

And according to the ETtoday.net, there are still more than 100 Wuhan tourists in Taiwan. Relevant authorities have tracked down the tour group's travel route and the people they have contacted, but these 100 tourists are also unable to return home because of the closure of the city of Wuhan, it seems "strange" to stay in Taiwan, and we'll see how it goes.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Taiwan's Ministry of Health and Welfare held a press conference to explain the spread of new pneumonia in Taiwan (picture: TVBS) 

While there are about 4,000 Taiwanese businessmen in Hubei and about 2,000 in Wuhan, almost all of them will return to Taiwan for the Lunar New Year, which will also become a major challenge in epidemic prevention. According to the regulations, if symptoms occur within 14 days after returning to Taiwan from Wuhan, they must be notified. If the illness is concealed and quarantine is evaded, a fine of NT $10,000 to nt $150,000(about 2,300 to 34,600 yuan) shall be imposed in accordance with Article 69 of the Law on the prevention and control of infectious diseases.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The Washington Post reports that the United States has begun screening Atlanta and Chicago airports for the new virus

On January 21, the COVID-19 announced the first case of new pneumonia in Seattle, Washington, with a confirmed case in the United States.

According to a report by the Seattle Times, the man, a resident of Snohomish county in Washington State, was in his 30s. He returned to the United States from Wuhan on the 15th. After landing, he felt unwell and contacted medical staff on his own. He is now in stable condition, observe treatment at Providence Regional Medical Center in Everett, Wash. .

Since last week, three airports in the United States -- JFK, lax and San Francisco -- have announced that they will begin screening passengers flying from Wuhan to the United States for temperature and symptoms, as of today, 1,200 people have been screened and no carriers have been found. CHICAGO, Atlanta International Airport recently joined the team of detailed screening. But the U. S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention says the virus poses little threat to the American public.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The New York Times has dispatched Chris Buckley, China's top reporter, to the front line in Wuhan, where the number of infected people is being updated on the front page.

The latest report focused on the city's closure, with a subtitle saying: After the death toll doubled, the central Chinese city of Wuhan banned flights and trains. In the first paragraph of the text, "17 deaths" were announced, mostly of elderly people with health problems.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A police officer stands guard at Hankou Railway Station in Wuhan, China

The New York Times has a few "caveats" about viruses:

Authorities have banned travel to more cities, affecting millions of people

Residents of Wuhan are anxious, some angry;

Who are the affected people?

What is coronavirus and why is it so dangerous?

"Feeling extremely powerless this time, " warned one SARS expert.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Screenshot of a CNBC report

The virus is expected to cause a loss of 1.4 billion yuan ($210 million) at the box office, according to CNBC, the US consumer news and business channel, "The worst is yet to come, " warns Larry Hu, an economist at Macquarie Capital.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe has released a report on the detection of new-type pneumonia

There is a case of infection in neighboring Japan. The official Japanese media have paid close attention to the epidemic in Wuhan. The information and the domestic news are almost in sync. They are basically following up the infection situation and the government's measures from an objective and neutral perspective.

According to NHK, Japanese Prime Minister Shinzō Abe said at a cabinet meeting on January 21 that he would carry out a thorough inspection of Chinese entry personnel if there were confirmed cases of infection, it will be sent to the Institute of Medical Science for further testing and control of people in close contact with infected people.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Face masks are on sale at a Japanese drug store with the words "go China" on the front

There are plenty of masks and other hygiene products, and there is no xenophobia or panic. Aside from the fact that all airport staff wear masks, there is virtually no impact in the city.

There is a story about a Weibo user that is moving. @ YDDOIT  : While studying in Japan, today I saw a Japanese man buying only three packs of face masks. The cashier asked him why he only bought so many. He said there were so many Chinese students in the neighborhood, they just bought it and they didn't have it.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
同时日本专家白鸥大学教授冈田晴惠，在节目《ひるおび！》中表示中国这次对应疫情的速度很惊人，仅1个月的时间就确认了新型病毒，并将病毒的具体信息迅速地公开报告出来。“从科学的角度看十分厉害，在仅有27名感染者的情况下就能发现且定性新型病毒，中国的研究人员和疾病预防和控制中心都是非常优秀的。”

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Wuhan has 38 weekly flights between Tokyo's Narita International Airport, Kansai International Airport, Central Airport and Fukuoka Airport, according to the Ministry of Land, Infrastructure and Transport (Korea) . Masks were distributed free of charge to passengers on flights between Narita International Airport and Wuhan, while in-flight announcements repeatedly advised passengers to wear masks and all crew members to work wearing masks and gloves.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Japan topped the list of travel destinations for the Lunar New Year holiday, with several media outlets expressing concern about the spread of the virus in the country ahead of the Spring Festival travel peak, according to a Chinese travel willingness survey.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The convenience store in Osaka, Japan, has an ample supply of face masks

The new virus has been splashed across international news in Japan, but there has not been much public interest in the case. Supplies of hygiene products such as face masks are plentiful, and there is no xenophobia or panic. Apart from the fact that all airport staff wear masks, there is virtually no impact in the city.

The Jan. 23 Asahi Shimbun, citing a "state of total war" announced at a meeting of municipal government officials in Wuhan, said that although the COVID-19 had been discovered 16 days earlier on Jan. 7, its infectivity and toxicity remained unknown. Most experts agree that it is less infectious and toxic than Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome and Middle East Respiratory Syndrome. However, because the virus can change its characteristics and increase its infectivity and toxicity, it still needs to be treated with caution.

Several media outlets fear that the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo will be affected by the outbreak, and the city's Olympic Organizing Committee has suspended the boxing qualifiers in Wuhan in February.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The Guardian's front page COVID-19

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Reports of the pneumonia outbreak in Wuhan appeared on the BBC's Youtube Front page

As of China Standard Time, there were four suspected cases of COVID-19 pneumonia in the UK, according to the Daily Mail. The four are Chinese tourists from Wuhan who are being treated under quarantine.

In fact, long before the emergence of suspected cases, the British BBC, The Sun and other media, published an appeal: The United Kingdom also can not take it lightly!

Especially after Wuhan was closed on the 23rd, the news of Harrie and Meggen has given way to COVID-19 on mainstream UK media websites, with news of the New China coronavirus making headlines.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The BBC news video shows the temperature at a public transport station in Wuhan

There are three main categories of coverage: Updates on the latest developments in China, reports on a range of preventive measures in the UK, and invitations for experts to interpret the Covid-19 for Popular Science.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At London's Heathrow Airport, a British passenger who had just returned from a flight in Wuhan described his journey to reporters

According to a report by the BBC, The Guardian and other British media on the 21st, the Department of Health will monitor the direct flight from Wuhan to London Heathrow, and medical teams will be in the remote area of Terminal T4 to check on relevant personnel.

However, with Wuhan's "closure" measures, the flight has now been suspended.

After that, there may be rain, snow and a big drop in temperature in the UK, which is the height of the flu season. Niko Phin, deputy director of the Department of Health, urged: "If people develop respiratory symptoms within 14 days of a visit to Wuhan, whether you are in China or have returned to the UK, please seek medical assistance! "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"Railway and shipping cut off from Wuhan, " Time's "pneumonia special" reports

January 22-23, the German major media have "aircraft and train outage" , "China cut off foreign traffic in Wuhan" as the theme, reported the Wuhan "closed" News. The foreign media sent to Wuhan focused on the daily life of the citizens after the city's traffic shutdown, as well as the operation of the major hospitals in Wuhan.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Ulf Roeller is a special correspondent for ZDF Channel 2 in Germany

Ulf Roeller, a special correspondent for ZDF Channel 2 in Germany, for example, is taking a first-hand look at how the city is doing, visiting residential areas and staking out late into the night outside the Wuhan Medical Center.

Deutsche Welle's report began with "fears of a new type of pneumonia. "

Deutsche Welle reporters also interviewed a number of passersby on the street to find out about supplies. Few passersby were reported in the city, and reporters on the front line mostly spoke of "Angst" about the COVID-19.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
WHO Chairman Dr Tan Desai at a press conference on the 23rd

The risk to the population in Germany is now low, according to estimates by the Robert Koch, which specialises in disease prevention. Meanwhile, several media outlets have referred to the delay by the World Health Organization (WHO) in deciding whether the current outbreak constitutes a "Global public Health Emergency of international concern. ". Local time, 23, World Health Organization Organization will continue to meet to discuss.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
German radio and TV station COVID-19 reports "Wuhan Railway and aircraft shutdown. " 

On January 23rd the Deutschlandradio singled out immigration related problems.

A spokesman for the Tourism Industry Association, DRV, said it had been in close contact with the Federal Foreign Office to monitor the situation. Lufthansa spokesman said the corresponding emergency measures can start at any time. The Airport Association ADV also said it had made detailed plans in case of an emergency.

In addition, medical teams are expected to be deployed to certain airports in the UK and Italy to deal specifically with passengers from Wuhan, China.

According to the World Health Organization, Germany's five airports must assume the "protection of public health" core capacity. The five cities are Hamburg, Düsseldorf, Frankfurt, Munich and Berlin. If a suspicious COVID-19 case is detected on the flight, they will be transported to the five airports, where medical support will be provided by the appropriate medical staff.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Virologist Christian Drosten speaks to the German Daily News

German Daily News (Tagschau) at noon on January 21 interview with a well-known German virologist, Berlin Charit Hospital Professor Christiane Drosten (Drosten) , "It's a new SARS coronavirus, but we don't know much about it yet, " he said

Here are some of the key messages Professor Drosten mentions:

From the virological point of view, this is a new type of SARS coronavirus. We have made a lot of discoveries about SARS in the past, so we have saved a lot of basic research. On the other hand, we must have a new understanding of the shape of the disease.

Global transmission is possible, and we know very little about the disease. I don't know if that means it's going to catch on.

The subject of SARS is thought to be over for good and the virus has been eliminated. Now, it returns to another variant. We can already imagine that it might come from a similar source, the same wild animal.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Electron microscopic examination of a coronavirus stained

As for drugs, we've done a lot of work with SARS, but vaccines are very complex.

Not only in China, but also in the northern hemisphere in the middle of the flu season. Many patients have symptoms that look very similar to the virus flu. We have to test the samples in the laboratory to see if it is caused by this new virus.

From where I sit, it makes sense to be overly cautious right now. Because we know so little, and we see that the whole thing is obviously spreading very quickly, very quickly.
